## Sample (deterministic seed=1 stride sample over sorted paths)

- screen/   : 438 PNG available, 50 sampled
- photo/mixed (unsplash, nasa, noaa, national-park-service, epa,
  internet-archive-scans, skitter, office-documents):
              329 PNG/JPG available, 100 sampled
- decode-failed/skipped: 3 (PNGs the image 0.25 png decoder rejected)
- images scored: 147

## Method

For each image, run BOTH entry points with FeatureSet::SUPPORTED:
  full  = analyze_features            (no gating)
  gated = analyze_with_dispatch_plan  (Stage 0/1.5/2)
Gate firing is read from the FULL-analysis signals (is_grayscale,
uniformity) — the same signals the dispatch plan reads internally from
Tier 1. For each feature a gate WOULD drop, record the value the FULL
analysis computed on images where the gate condition fired
(counterfactual safety assessment — independent of whether the plan
currently ACTS on that gate). Ground-truth chroma is measured directly
from RGB8 bytes (max-min channel spread per pixel), independent of the
analyzer's is_grayscale classifier, to detect grayscale-gate misfires.

A gate is SAFE iff every would-drop feature is consistently negligible on
the images where its condition fired. "Negligible" uses a PER-FEATURE
line: |full value| < 1.0 for unbounded features (laplacian/aq
percentiles up to 255), and |full value| < 0.27 for [0,1]-valued
fraction features (patch_fraction*) — 0.27 is feature.rs's documented
screen-like operating threshold, so a 0.99 there is maximal signal, not
noise. A flat 1.0 line would silently pass a maximal patch_fraction drop.

## Result (per the GATE VALIDATION SUMMARY on stderr)

GRAYSCALE gate (CHROMA_DROP_FEATURES) — VALIDATED-SAFE, shipped ENABLED
  condition fire rate:            8/147 (5.4%)
  worst-case would-drop magnitude: 0.000000 (every chroma feature)
  meaningful would-drop events:   0
  misfires (fired on real-chroma image): 0  (cross-checked vs ground-truth)
  => On strict R==G==B grayscale the dropped chroma features are
     bit-exactly their default; classifier never fired on coloured
     content. Safe to drop.

UNIFORMITY gate — NAIVE uniformity>0.95 (SATURATING_DROP_FEATURES) —
                  UNSAFE on this sample, correctly shipped DISABLED
  condition fire rate:            10/147 (6.8%)
  worst-case would-drop magnitude: 255.000000 (laplacian_variance_peak)
  meaningful would-drop events:   42  (per-feature line: 1.0 unbounded,
                                       0.27 for patch_fraction*)
  worst offending: laplacian_variance_peak=255.0 on
    screen/1440x900/proofwiki__pythagoras__1440x900__dpr1.png
  => The issue-#53 spec assumed uniformity>0.95 ⇒ Laplacian percentiles
     pin to ~0 and patch_fraction_fast won't vary. That holds for
     PHOTOGRAPHIC flat content but is VIOLATED on text / line-art /
     document / diagram screen content: a mostly-white page with
     sparse-but-maximally-sharp black text reports uniformity>0.95 yet
     has laplacian_variance_peak=255, laplacian_variance_p99 up to 38,
     patch_fraction_fast≈0.99, aq_map_p99 up to 5.9. Dropping these
     discards the single most discriminating line-art / text signals —
     exactly the screen-content class the picker most needs.

UNIFORMITY gate — CONTENT-AWARE uniformity>0.95 AND edge_density<tau
                  (PR #54 calibration attempt) — NO SAFE THRESHOLD FOUND,
                  shipped DISABLED
  Hypothesis (PR brief): text/line-art keeps high tier1 edge_density even
  when "uniform"; flat-photo goes to ~0. A gate of `uniformity>0.95 AND
  edge_density<tau` would then fire only on safe flat-photo content.

  REFUTED by the imazen-26 distribution on two counts:

  (1) The uniformity>0.95 subset contains ZERO flat-photo images and
      10/10 document/text/line-art images (ground-truth fingerprint:
      laplacian_variance_peak>=64 OR patch_fraction_fast>=0.5). There is
      no safe population for the gate to fire on — the naive gate is pure
      information loss.
        [TEXT/LINE-ART] n=10  edge_density min=0.00000 median=0.00424
                              max=0.00940 ; variance min=0.001 median=78.6
                              max=2280.8
        [FLAT-PHOTO]    n=0

  (2) edge_density does NOT separate the classes: the text-like set
      spans edge_density [0.0, 0.0094], INCLUDING a near-blank page
      (screen/1920x1080/wikipedia__einstein, edge_density=0.0,
      variance=7e-4) whose ONE non-default signal is
      patch_fraction_fast=0.994 — the documented AUC-0.880
      screen-vs-photo discriminator (feature.rs §PatchFraction; screens
      p50=0.726, photos p50=0.002). Any tau tight enough to fire on it
      still drops the picker's single most discriminating feature.

  Threshold sweep (edge_density_max, meaningful-drop events on fired set):
        tau=1e-4 : fired 1, UNSAFE (drops patch_fraction_fast=0.994)
        tau=5e-4 : fired 1, UNSAFE (same)
        tau=1e-3 : fired 4, UNSAFE (drops laplacian_variance_peak=255)
        tau=2e-3 : fired 4, UNSAFE
        tau=5e-3 : fired 7, UNSAFE
  Every tested tau is UNSAFE. VERDICT: no safe content-aware uniformity
  gate on this corpus — keep ENABLE_UNIFORMITY_GATE=false (grayscale-gate
  only). SATURATING_DROP_FEATURES retained for a future revisit on a
  corpus that contains uniform PHOTOGRAPHIC content.

  Note on the safety line: patch_fraction* is [0,1]-valued, so a flat
  MEANINGFUL_MAGNITUDE=1.0 would mis-classify a maximal 0.99 drop as
  "safe". meaningful_threshold() uses the operating threshold 0.27 for
  patch_fraction* (feature.rs flags screen-like at >=0.27).

## TSV columns

path, stratum, width, height, is_grayscale, uniformity, edge_density,
variance, chroma_frac_gt2 (fraction of sampled px with channel spread >
2 levels), max_channel_spread, gray_gate_fired, uniformity_gate_fired
(naive), content_unif_gate_fired (content-aware, uniformity>0.95 AND
edge_density<tau), n_chroma_dropped (plan actually dropped),
n_saturating_dropped (plan actually dropped; 0 — both uniformity gates
disabled), gray_gate_misfire, then drop_C_<feature> columns (full value
on grayscale-condition-fired images) and drop_S_<feature> columns (full
value on uniformity-condition-fired images).
